<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880804-0011 </DOCNO><HL> What's News -- Business and Finance </HL><SO>  </SO><TEXT>   THE TRADE BILL CLEARED the Senate 85-11 and was sent to Reagan, who is expected to sign it. The measure, which is designed to open foreign markets to more U.S. goods and boost domestic industries, was finally embraced by both Democrats and Republicans. The revised legislation is largely stripped of the protectionism it first contained.    ---   Argentina may soon get an emergency $500 million loan from the U.S. to pay overdue interest on its foreign bank debt, sources said. But delays in negotiating the loan may still force U.S. banks to classify the debt as nonperforming, hurting their profits.    ---   Racketeering charges could be handed up today against people involved in transactions between Princeton/Newport Partners, an investment firm with ties to others implicated in Wall Street's insider-trading scandal, and Drexel.    ---   Eastern Airlines suffered another major setback as a federal judge temporarily blocked the carrier's plan to slash its flight operations and lay off 4,000 employees. The injunction was sought by Eastern's unions.    ---   Hollywood writers reached a tentative accord in their 22-week strike, which has virtually paralyzed movie and TV production. Writers Guild members are expected to vote on the proposed pact over the weekend and could return to work on Monday.    ---   The Fed approved new minimum capital guidelines for U.S. banks and banking firms, implementing a recent accord with 11 other nations. Several money-center banks will have to boost their capital by up to $15 billion.    ---   U.S. car sales jumped 6.9% in late July, continuing a recent boom. The strong showing by domestic makers offset disappointing results for importers. For the full month, sales were even with the year-ago period.    ---   Ford Motor is considering building new plants because sales growth is being hurt by a lack of manufacturing capacity. Such a move would be a major strategic shift by Ford.    ---   Shell Oil said unusually rapid corrosion in an eight-inch pipe led to the May 5 explosion at a Louisiana refinery that killed seven and sharply curtailed the company's operations.    ---   First RepublicBank's credit-card unit was seized by bank regulators, part of a bailout that may cost up to a record $3 billion, an official said.    ---   OPEC's price-monitoring panel instructed the oil cartel's new secretary-general to negotiate production discipline throughout the group.    ---   The SEC is investigating a California real estate investor in connection with extensive trading in stocks linked to Business Week articles.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 203,590,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2134.07, up 2.85; transportation 887.84, off 3.74; utilities 183.44, up 1.07.    Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 1231.06, off 3.65.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.24, up 1.39; spot index 130.40, off 0.66.    Dollar: 132.75 yen, off 0.23; 1.8756 marks, off 0.0017. </TEXT></DOC>